504":"1410–1504","18 May 1460":"18 mei 1460","1473":"1473","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1434":"1434","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1521":"1521","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","1427":"1427","1504":"1504","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","South Mylles, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1434–1475":"1434–1475","1429–1473":"1429–1473","1432–1521":"1432–1521","1434–1496":"1434–1496","1436–1490":"1436–1490","1445–Male":"1445–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1460–1521":"1460–1521","1406–1477":"1406–1477","1410–1504":"1410–1504","18 May 1460":"18 May 1460","1473":"1473","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1434":"1434","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1521":"1521","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","1427":"1427","1504":"1504","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","South Mylles, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":21,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Spencer Gentleman was born in 1434, in Bedfordshire, England, his father, Robert Spencer of Colmworth, was 28 and his mother, Anna Smythe, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. John Spencer. He died in 1475, in Towcester, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1434–1475":"1434–1475","1429–1473":"1429–1473","1432–1521":"1432–1521","1434–1496":"1434–1496","1436–1490":"1436–1490","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1460–1521":"1460–1521","1406–1477":"1406–1477","1410–1504":"1410–1504","18 May 1460":"18. mai 1460","1473":"1473","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1434":"1434","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1521":"1521","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","1427":"1427","1504":"1504","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","South Mylles, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Cople, Bedfordshire, England":"Cople, Bedfordshire, England","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1434–1475":"1434–1475","1429–1473":"1429–1473","1432–1521":"1432–1521","1434–1496":"1434–1496","1436–1490":"1436–1490","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1460–1521":"1460–1521","1406–1477":"1406–1477","1410–1504":"1410–1504","18 May 1460":"18. toukokuuta 1460","1473":"1473","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","1434":"1434","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1521":"1521","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1475":"1475","1496":"1496","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","1427":"1427","1504":"1504","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","South Mylles, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford